{"parse":{"title":"Miller Richardson","pageid":44810363,"revid":830819770,"text":{"*":"<div class=\"mw-parser-output\"><table class=\"infobox biography vcard\" style=\"width:22em\"><tbody><tr><th colspan=\"2\" style=\"text-align:center;font-size:125%;font-weight:bold\"><span class=\"fn\">Miller Richardson</span></th></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Born</th><td>\n<span class=\"birthplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/El_Paso,_Texas\" title=\"El Paso, Texas\">El Paso, Texas</a></span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Died</th><td>\n<span class=\"deathplace\"><a href=\"/wiki/Staten_Island,_New_York\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Staten Island, New York\">Staten Island, New York</a></span></td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Occupation</th><td class=\"role\">\nVisual artist, stage and costume designer, scenographer, choreographer</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\">Years&#160;active</th><td>\n1953 - 2007</td></tr><tr><th scope=\"row\"><span class=\"nowrap\">Partner(s)</span></th><td>\n<a href=\"/wiki/Flower_Hujer\" title=\"Flower Hujer\">Flower Hujer</a></td></tr></tbody></table>\n<p><b>Miller Richardson</b> (1917 &#8211; May 25, 2012) was an American visual artist, stage and costume designer, scenographer and modern dance choreographer best known for his collaborations with <a href=\"/wiki/Flower_Hujer\" title=\"Flower Hujer\">Flower Hujer</a> in the Flower Hujer Dance Theater company.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"Life_and_career\">Life and career</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Miller_Richardson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=1\" title=\"Edit section: Life and career\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<p>William Miller Richardson, known professionally as Miller Richardson, was born  in El Paso, Texas.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-1\">&#91;1&#93;</a></sup>  He studied architecture at the <a href=\"/wiki/Georgia_Institute_of_Technology\" title=\"Georgia Institute of Technology\">Georgia Institute of Technology</a>. At 19 he was awarded a scholarship to study art at the <a href=\"/wiki/Art_Students_League\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Art Students League\">Art Students League</a> under <a href=\"/wiki/William_Charles_McNulty\" title=\"William Charles McNulty\">William Charles McNulty</a>. He also studied at the <a href=\"/wiki/Museum_of_Design_Atlanta\" title=\"Museum of Design Atlanta\">Museum of Design Atlanta</a> during 1938.\n</p><p>In 1953 he met choreographer and dancer <a href=\"/wiki/Flower_Hujer\" title=\"Flower Hujer\">Flower Hujer</a>, who is described in his obituary as his \"longtime companion\".<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-2\">&#91;2&#93;</a></sup> In 1975 they bought a neo-Gothic house together in New Brighton, Pendleton Place, which he restored. According to the New York Times: \"His garden is exquisite, with shaped fir trees that give it an Italian air.\"<sup id=\"cite_ref-3\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-3\">&#91;3&#93;</a></sup> They lived there the rest of their lives. He collaborated with Hujer as artistic director of the Flower Hujer Dance Theatre, where he worked on choreography, costume and lighting design and sometimes performed. Richardson and Hujer were known for their exotic costumes and creative choreography. In 1984 he did a demonstration of costume design at <a href=\"/wiki/Lincoln_Center\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Lincoln Center\">Lincoln Center</a>.<sup id=\"cite_ref-4\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-4\">&#91;4&#93;</a></sup> Their dances, based on religious and nature themes and praised for their dignity and simplicity, were presented in <a href=\"/wiki/Trinity_Wall_Street\" class=\"mw-redirect\" title=\"Trinity Wall Street\">Trinity Wall Street</a>, <a href=\"/wiki/St._Bartholomew%27s_Episcopal_Church_(Manhattan)\" title=\"St. Bartholomew&#39;s Episcopal Church (Manhattan)\">St. Bartholomew's</a>,<sup id=\"cite_ref-5\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-5\">&#91;5&#93;</a></sup> <a href=\"/wiki/Church_of_the_Intercession_(Manhattan)\" title=\"Church of the Intercession (Manhattan)\">Church of the Intercession (Manhattan)</a>, Choreospace and other venues. Their best known piece was \"<a href=\"/wiki/Le_Jongleur_de_Notre_Dame\" title=\"Le Jongleur de Notre Dame\">The Juggler of Our Lady</a>\", based on a medieval legend turned into a story by <a href=\"/wiki/Anatole_France\" title=\"Anatole France\">Anatole France</a>. It was broadcast on television in 1965, performed in Kennebunk, Maine, in 1967,<sup id=\"cite_ref-6\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"#cite_note-6\">&#91;6&#93;</a></sup> and had revivals in 1981, 1988 and 1990.\n</p><p>Richardson worked as a multi-media artist. In addition to working in the theater, painting settings, backdrops and decor, he also executed commissions like portraits, murals, and decorative projects. He did not retire until he was nearly 90.\n</p>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"References\">References</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Miller_Richardson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=2\" title=\"Edit section: References\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<div class=\"reflist\" style=\"list-style-type: decimal;\">\n<div class=\"mw-references-wrap\"><ol class=\"references\">\n<li id=\"cite_note-1\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-1\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.silive.com/obituaries/index.ssf/2012/08/william_miller_richardson_95.html\">http://www.silive.com/obituaries/index.ssf/2012/08/william_miller_richardson_95.html</a> | Obituary</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-2\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-2\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"http://www.luckyrabbitestatesales.com/apps/blog/show/26940257-the-antique-estate-sale-of-the-decade-\">http://www.luckyrabbitestatesales.com/apps/blog/show/26940257-the-antique-estate-sale-of-the-decade-</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-3\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-3\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/21/realestate/streetscapes-pendleton-place-3-houses-that-recall-19th-century-staten-island.html\">https://www.nytimes.com/1997/12/21/realestate/streetscapes-pendleton-place-3-houses-that-recall-19th-century-staten-island.html</a></span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-4\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-4\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Dance, New York Magazine, October 29, p. 113</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-5\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-5\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\">Dance, New York Magazine, December 5, 1988, p. 344</span>\n</li>\n<li id=\"cite_note-6\"><span class=\"mw-cite-backlink\"><b><a href=\"#cite_ref-6\">^</a></b></span> <span class=\"reference-text\"><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https://newspaperarchive.com/us/maine/biddeford/biddeford-journal/1967/08-14/page-2%7C\">https://newspaperarchive.com/us/maine/biddeford/biddeford-journal/1967/08-14/page-2%7C</a> Interfaith Service Ends Arts Festival, Biddeford Journal: Monday, August 14, 1967 - Page 2</span>\n</li>\n</ol></div></div>\n<h2><span class=\"mw-headline\" id=\"External_links\">External links</span><span class=\"mw-editsection\"><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">[</span><a href=\"/w/index.php?title=Miller_Richardson&amp;action=edit&amp;section=3\" title=\"Edit section: External links\">edit</a><span class=\"mw-editsection-bracket\">]</span></span></h2>\n<ul><li><a rel=\"nofollow\" class=\"external free\" href=\"https://www.1stdibs.com/cre